00:11:40.530 --> 00:11:43.400
128 by 128 when you're looking
at the browser view in Finder

00:11:43.400 --> 00:11:46.020
and you select an application,
don't double click it but

00:11:46.020 --> 00:11:48.850
just select it or a document,
you see the enlarged

00:11:48.870 --> 00:11:51.660
application icon in Finder,
right?

00:11:51.720 --> 00:11:55.720
And application icons and document icons
on Mac OS X are extremely rich in design,

00:11:55.720 --> 00:11:57.240
in visual appearance.

00:11:57.240 --> 00:11:59.190
And they have lots of characteristics.

00:11:59.230 --> 00:12:01.420
And if you look at this
particular slide on the top row,

00:12:01.530 --> 00:12:06.490
you've got user applications
which are highly,

00:12:06.490 --> 00:12:09.940
you know, they have lots of color,
they're inviting, they're attractive,

00:12:09.940 --> 00:12:13.040
they communicate lots about
what the application does.

00:12:13.100 --> 00:12:17.240
That's the first genre of applications,
first type of application icons.

00:12:17.240 --> 00:12:20.080
The second row is utility applications.

00:12:20.080 --> 00:12:22.720
They're monochromatic in color.

00:12:22.720 --> 00:12:25.990
They're viewed in characteristics,
visual characteristics, right?

00:12:26.040 --> 00:12:29.520
In fact, there's a lot to say about icons
and I'm not even the expert there.

00:12:29.540 --> 00:12:31.490
And I don't want to go into any
great detail because I could

00:12:31.490 --> 00:12:32.960
talk this whole session about it.

00:12:32.960 --> 00:12:35.390
So we've actually put a session
specifically aside to talk

00:12:35.460 --> 00:12:38.060
about icons here in Hall 2,
10:30 on Friday.

00:12:39.940 --> 00:12:43.570
And the biggest takeaway from this
session is going to be that you will

00:12:43.570 --> 00:12:47.120
learn how to critique icons in Mac OS X.

00:12:47.140 --> 00:12:48.800
So that when you're working
with a graphic design

00:12:48.820 --> 00:12:51.900
agency or graphic designer,
or in-house graphic designer,

00:12:51.900 --> 00:12:54.580
and they produce a first
turn of an icon and say,

00:12:54.580 --> 00:12:56.820
"Hey, what do you think of this
new icon?" You can say,

00:12:56.820 --> 00:12:58.360
"Well, you know, I don't know.

00:12:58.360 --> 00:13:00.640
Either it's great, or it's not,
or it needs some more work."

00:13:00.640 --> 00:13:03.030
So I think coming to this session is
going to give you that information,

00:13:03.030 --> 00:13:05.190
give you some insight into
how to critique icons and

00:13:05.190 --> 00:13:07.030
make some good choices.

00:13:07.090 --> 00:13:10.210
Icons are very different on Mac OS X,
and they're a very visual

00:13:10.210 --> 00:13:13.840
component of your application,
so they're really a big deal.

00:13:14.920 --> 00:13:20.230
Conversations about the icon
inevitably lead to the doc,

00:13:20.230 --> 00:13:20.230
because the doc is the keeper of icons,
right?

00:13:20.740 --> 00:13:25.190
And there are three things that you
need to do with respect to the dock,

00:13:25.210 --> 00:13:27.520
or that you need to pay attention
to with respect to the dock,

00:13:27.520 --> 00:13:30.800
in terms of delivering a great user
experience on 10 with your application.

00:13:30.850 --> 00:13:33.800
The first two things are
things that you must do.

00:13:33.830 --> 00:13:37.850
Every application on the platform
should do the first two things,

00:13:37.930 --> 00:13:40.820
and we're going to talk
about these in detail.

00:13:40.820 --> 00:13:44.850
The third thing is something
that some applications should do.

00:13:44.850 --> 00:13:48.850
In some instances, it really makes sense
to animate a dock icon,

00:13:48.850 --> 00:13:49.270
but not in every case.

00:13:50.300 --> 00:13:54.400
So the first thing that every application
that ships on Mac OS X should do

00:13:54.500 --> 00:13:57.440
is to respect the doc's location.

00:13:57.510 --> 00:14:00.690
Why does this matter?

00:14:00.690 --> 00:14:00.690
Well,

00:14:01.010 --> 00:14:04.150
Everybody's been caught currently,
because lots of

00:14:04.160 --> 00:14:10.060
applications don't do this,
currently with windows that size behind

00:14:10.060 --> 00:14:15.040
the dock and now suddenly you're caught
because you've got to move the dock

00:14:15.040 --> 00:14:15.040
or size it down or whatever you do to
get at the resize box for the window.

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:18.790
So every application on Mac OS X that
ships should respect the dock's location.

00:14:18.800 --> 00:14:21.160
There are APIs available
for Carbon and Cocoa,

00:14:21.220 --> 00:14:25.310
and when you open a new window or open
a user window or zoom your window,

00:14:25.310 --> 00:14:28.200
make sure that you don't zoom
it or size it behind the dock.

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:30.600
So this is the behavior
that you want to have.

00:14:30.730 --> 00:14:31.690
Not this.

00:14:32.080 --> 00:14:33.560
This.

00:14:34.180 --> 00:14:36.460
users will be a lot less frustrated,
and you're going to provide a

00:14:36.460 --> 00:14:39.100
greater user experience for them.

00:14:39.250 --> 00:14:43.080
The next thing that every application
should do to provide a great user

00:14:43.080 --> 00:14:49.580
experience on Mac OS X is to have
dot clicks always produce a window.

00:14:49.650 --> 00:14:50.890
Why is this so important?

00:14:50.920 --> 00:14:54.140
Well, one of the things that we're trying
to get around with in Aqua is to

00:14:54.140 --> 00:14:57.830
move beyond where we were with
Mac OS 9 and provide a better,

00:14:57.830 --> 00:14:59.720
more streamlined user experience.

00:14:59.780 --> 00:15:01.140
Not all the features are there yet.

00:15:01.140 --> 00:15:01.760
We know that.

00:15:01.800 --> 00:15:03.920
We're consistently revising
the operating system.

00:15:03.920 --> 00:15:06.220
We're going to add new functionality.

00:15:06.800 --> 00:15:09.760
But one of the things that's an
experience that we've probably all had

00:15:09.930 --> 00:15:14.120
with someone on the Macintosh is where
people close the document window thinking

00:15:14.120 --> 00:15:16.140
that they're quitting the application.

00:15:16.180 --> 00:15:18.240
And suddenly they're sitting
there now and there's no

00:15:18.240 --> 00:15:19.520
windows open on the machine.

00:15:19.640 --> 00:15:23.370
They click on the background,
the desktop on Mac OS 9,

00:15:23.380 --> 00:15:24.360
and they're lost.

00:15:24.420 --> 00:15:25.500
Where'd my application go?

00:15:25.610 --> 00:15:26.420
Where'd my document go?

00:15:26.420 --> 00:15:28.260
I don't know what I did.

00:15:28.480 --> 00:15:31.050
And one of our design goals for
the doc and for this particular

00:15:31.050 --> 00:15:35.360
principle is to make sure that that
doesn't happen anymore on Mac OS X.

00:15:35.360 --> 00:15:38.190
And if every developer out there
shipping a product on Mac OS X does this,

00:15:38.390 --> 00:15:39.600
The problem's going to be gone.

00:15:39.630 --> 00:15:41.330
Because what happens is
if you follow the rules,

00:15:41.400 --> 00:15:45.320
if you're a document-based application,
if you have no document windows open,

00:15:45.330 --> 00:15:48.790
a click on the doc will result in a new,
untitled document.

00:15:49.720 --> 00:15:54.660
If all of your windows are minimized,
a click on the dock is going to activate

00:15:54.660 --> 00:15:57.440
the last window that was minimized.

00:15:57.490 --> 00:15:59.240
And if you're a
non-document-based application,

00:15:59.240 --> 00:16:01.770
like System Preferences, for example,
and you close the

00:16:01.800 --> 00:16:03.700
System Preferences window,
when you click on the

00:16:03.790 --> 00:16:05.840
System Preferences icon,
the app is still running, right?

00:16:05.900 --> 00:16:09.500
What it does is it brings
up its main window.

00:16:09.540 --> 00:16:13.250
That's the behavior that every
application on Mac OS X should be doing.

00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:19.860
Animating Doc Icons This is the third
thing that relates to the doc and

00:16:19.860 --> 00:16:24.900
this falls into the category of things
that some applications should do.

00:16:24.900 --> 00:16:28.630
Every application could animate,
it's possible to animate your

00:16:28.630 --> 00:16:31.100
application icon and your document icon.

00:16:31.100 --> 00:16:33.580
And this should only be done in
the case where you want to provide

00:16:33.580 --> 00:16:34.900
meaningful feedback to the user.

00:16:34.900 --> 00:16:38.300
You want to provide status and
some operation that's occurring.

00:16:38.300 --> 00:16:42.130
You want to provide some update as to,
you know, progress on some,

00:16:42.180 --> 00:16:46.100
maybe a high-end rendering process that's
taking place with one of the documents.

00:16:46.200 --> 00:16:49.200
So when you consider
animating your doc icon,

00:16:49.200 --> 00:16:52.390
whether it's your document,
a document icon, or an application icon,

00:16:52.400 --> 00:16:55.430
think very carefully about whether
this is going to provide great

00:16:55.540 --> 00:16:59.100
value to the user in terms of
indicating progress or status,

00:16:59.100 --> 00:17:01.820
or whether this is just something cool.

00:17:01.900 --> 00:17:05.440
This is the kind of functionality
that we dread making available

00:17:05.440 --> 00:17:08.700
sometimes because there's always
developers out there that go,

00:17:08.700 --> 00:17:11.000
"This is just too cool."
And they call home and they say,

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:11.300
"You know what?

00:17:11.300 --> 00:17:12.920
I've got to work on something
really important." And then

00:17:12.920 --> 00:17:14.450
they stay up all late,
late real night,

00:17:14.450 --> 00:17:15.700
making something really neat.

00:17:15.700 --> 00:17:17.200
And yet it has no value.

00:17:17.200 --> 00:17:20.600
And the last thing that any of us
want is firing up a bunch of apps

00:17:20.600 --> 00:17:24.190
and having the doc animating every
single icon in the doc animating.

00:17:24.330 --> 00:17:26.550
So do this where it makes,
it lends value.

00:17:26.830 --> 00:17:28.200
And don't use garish colors.

00:17:28.200 --> 00:17:29.160
Don't use blinking.

00:17:29.220 --> 00:17:32.250
Don't use, you know,
just some crazy animation

00:17:32.550 --> 00:17:34.190
that's constantly going.

00:17:34.200 --> 00:17:35.700
Use it where it adds value.

00:17:35.700 --> 00:17:38.440
So for example, in Mac OS X,
if you look at what we're doing

00:17:38.450 --> 00:17:40.630
with the mail application,
the mail application

00:17:40.630 --> 00:17:41.580
icon looks like this.

00:17:41.930 --> 00:17:45.200
And when you receive new mail,
that's a status that we want

00:17:45.200 --> 00:17:45.200
to communicate to the user.

00:17:45.200 --> 00:17:48.090
That's a situation we want
to communicate to the user.

00:17:48.200 --> 00:17:53.200
So what we do is we tag the
application icon with a red badge.

00:17:53.320 --> 00:17:57.600
The red badge happens to have inside
of it the number of new unread

00:17:57.600 --> 00:17:59.200
messages that you have in your inbox.

00:17:59.200 --> 00:18:01.690
But that's not what's
most important here.

00:18:01.700 --> 00:18:04.700
What's most important here is
that there's a red visual cue

00:18:04.700 --> 00:18:06.700
that your eye picks up on,
even if you're not even

00:18:06.700 --> 00:18:07.550
looking at the doc.

00:18:07.700 --> 00:18:08.700
You're on screen.

00:18:08.700 --> 00:18:10.040
You're interacting with your computer.

00:18:10.200 --> 00:18:14.270
And yet you see that red icon up here,
certainly if the doc is up.

00:18:14.400 --> 00:18:15.400
right?

00:18:15.660 --> 00:18:19.380
That's the kind of guideline that
we're looking to lay out for you,

00:18:19.380 --> 00:18:20.240
before you.

00:18:20.240 --> 00:18:22.540
Be very careful how you do animation.

00:18:22.540 --> 00:18:25.220
Do it in a way that's minimal,
minimalist,

00:18:25.220 --> 00:18:29.000
that doesn't get in the way and stand out
in a way that's going to distract users,

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.000
but that also communicates volumes.

00:18:31.020 --> 00:18:33.080
So what happens is your eye
sees a red dot and it goes,

00:18:33.080 --> 00:18:35.770
"Oh, I got new mail." And then you
zero on in the details as to how

00:18:35.770 --> 00:18:38.730
much mail and whether you really
care about reading it or not.

00:18:38.730 --> 00:18:41.680
So be careful how you choose
to animate your icons.

00:18:41.680 --> 00:18:45.330
And we're going to have sessions later on
this week that go into detail about how

00:18:45.330 --> 00:18:48.330
to do this from the API point of view,
but I don't want to get

00:18:48.460 --> 00:18:50.000
into those details here.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.450
So before we get into the next session,
I want to talk about

00:18:52.480 --> 00:18:53.820
what's your citizenship.

00:18:59.300 --> 00:19:04.930
I brought this up because I recently
moved to Silicon Valley from Canada.

00:19:05.100 --> 00:19:05.180
I'm a Canadian.

00:19:05.990 --> 00:19:08.690
And it's a great place to live here,
it really is.

00:19:08.920 --> 00:19:12.300
But you know,
and I'm not an American citizen,

00:19:12.300 --> 00:19:15.400
I'm a Canadian citizen, proudly so,
but I have a work visa here.

00:19:15.530 --> 00:19:18.500
But the thing about citizenship is,

00:19:26.600 --> 00:19:26.890
When I go around here,
particularly when we moved in

00:19:26.890 --> 00:19:27.230
and I started to drive around the
valley and find my way around,

00:19:27.230 --> 00:19:27.520
I couldn't find things.

00:19:27.520 --> 00:19:30.600
There were certain things I was
looking for and I couldn't find them.

00:19:30.600 --> 00:19:34.600
And it really came down to a cultural
difference or kind of like a citizenship.

00:19:34.600 --> 00:19:36.590
I mean they do things differently in
the States than they do in Canada.

00:19:36.690 --> 00:19:39.240
They do things differently in
Europe than they do in Canada or

00:19:39.240 --> 00:19:40.600
in the States or whatever.

00:19:40.710 --> 00:19:43.500
And so some prime examples of
looking for something and not

00:19:43.500 --> 00:19:46.590
finding it when I expected it
to be there were three things.

00:19:46.590 --> 00:19:48.600
First of all, service stations,
gas stations.

00:19:48.600 --> 00:19:50.060
I'm driving down the highway.

00:19:50.060 --> 00:19:53.000
I'm expecting a gas station to be
at an interchange where there's

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:54.560
another highway or whatever.

00:19:54.620 --> 00:19:55.600
That's where they are in Canada.

00:19:55.740 --> 00:19:57.550
And so we've gone on
trips here and we've,

00:19:57.550 --> 00:19:59.600
you know, been near running out of gas.

00:19:59.600 --> 00:20:01.600
And there's no service station.

00:20:01.600 --> 00:20:04.580
It's not the visual cues
that I expected are there,

00:20:04.650 --> 00:20:06.590
but there's no service station.

00:20:06.600 --> 00:20:08.470
The other thing is a 7-Eleven.

00:20:08.640 --> 00:20:09.600
I can't find 7-Elevens.

00:20:09.600 --> 00:20:10.590
They're not working.

00:20:10.630 --> 00:20:12.780
we're expectant to be.

00:20:13.890 --> 00:20:16.470
Usually in Canada, or in eastern Canada,
certainly the ones that I knew about,

00:20:16.610 --> 00:20:19.520
7-Elevens were by the local strip mall,
right?

00:20:19.550 --> 00:20:21.940
The small shopping plaza that's
in the neighbourhoods or whatever.

00:20:21.940 --> 00:20:23.440
There's always a 7-Eleven right there.

00:20:23.440 --> 00:20:24.960
Well, that's not where they are here.

00:20:24.960 --> 00:20:27.030
So I'm looking for
things in certain places,

00:20:27.030 --> 00:20:28.330
and I'm not finding them.

00:20:28.340 --> 00:20:29.690
And the other thing is lakes.

00:20:29.860 --> 00:20:33.280
Where I come from, in eastern Canada,
there's lakes everywhere.

00:20:33.280 --> 00:20:36.400
And so when I go into the woods,
go for a hike or whatever,

00:20:36.430 --> 00:20:39.010
and I'm walking around over the hills,
I expect to see a lake.

00:20:39.090 --> 00:20:40.140
And I do.

00:20:40.140 --> 00:20:43.180
And yet when I go for hikes here in
the Santa Cruz Mountains or whatever,

00:20:43.340 --> 00:20:46.960
there are numerous instances where we've
been at a children's camp or something,

00:20:46.960 --> 00:20:51.240
and we're walking around,
and we expect a lake to be somewhere,

00:20:51.240 --> 00:20:51.960
and there's no lakes.

00:20:51.960 --> 00:20:54.090
And it really disorients you.

00:20:54.110 --> 00:20:57.280
And the reason I'm talking about this is,
we showed the Mac OS X desktop

00:20:57.280 --> 00:20:58.860
at the beginning,
right?

00:20:58.860 --> 00:21:01.150
That's the world in which your
application is going to live.

00:21:01.220 --> 00:21:03.680
The question is,
will your application show

00:21:03.680 --> 00:21:06.060
things in the right places
where users expect them to be?

00:21:06.060 --> 00:21:08.990
What's your citizenship going to
be with your Mac OS X product?

00:21:11.030 --> 00:21:13.770
And the way to show what your
citizenship is through the

00:21:13.860 --> 00:21:15.090
next several building blocks.

00:21:15.190 --> 00:21:16.900
The first is system appearance.

00:21:16.980 --> 00:21:20.540
Aqua has very specific representation
of on-screen interface elements,

00:21:20.550 --> 00:21:20.900
right?

00:21:21.040 --> 00:21:23.320
Pop-ups look a certain way,
push buttons look a certain way,

00:21:23.400 --> 00:21:26.080
bevel buttons, radio buttons,
all of the interface widgets that

00:21:26.080 --> 00:21:29.860
we're used to have a particular
appearance that's unique on Mac OS X.

00:21:29.940 --> 00:21:31.360
They don't look grayscale.

00:21:31.420 --> 00:21:34.190
They don't look just white
or whatever we're used to

00:21:34.190 --> 00:21:35.490
previously on the Macintosh.

00:21:35.690 --> 00:21:37.000
They don't have other
platform appearances.

00:21:37.070 --> 00:21:39.300
They're very unique to Mac OS X.

00:21:39.360 --> 00:21:42.430
Your application needs to follow this
appearance if it's going to look like

00:21:42.470 --> 00:21:44.970
a full-class citizen on Mac OS X.

00:21:45.440 --> 00:21:48.420
The reason that's important is because
users are going to come to expect a

00:21:48.430 --> 00:21:52.770
particular appearance for controls,
and they're going to use that

00:21:52.770 --> 00:21:55.890
as visual cues for visual cues
as they search out things on the

00:21:55.890 --> 00:21:58.640
screen and know what to click on,
et cetera.

00:21:58.800 --> 00:22:01.660
So one of the new things that was
introduced with Mac OS X is toolbars.

00:22:01.810 --> 00:22:05.690
Toolbars in Mac OS X have a
striped background appearance.

00:22:05.690 --> 00:22:08.400
They have icons that are up
on the toolbar that have a

00:22:08.400 --> 00:22:10.370
shelf-like perspective on them.

00:22:10.510 --> 00:22:14.750
We're going to talk in detail about
what toolbar icons look like in the

00:22:14.760 --> 00:22:16.960
designing icon session on Friday.

00:22:17.200 --> 00:22:21.190
But Mac OS X toolbars have
a very special appearance.

00:22:21.260 --> 00:22:22.700
They're very cleanly laid out.

00:22:23.060 --> 00:22:24.700
Nice use of white space.

00:22:24.700 --> 00:22:26.700
The icons sit on a striped background,
as I said.

00:22:26.700 --> 00:22:30.140
There's text below the icon,
anti-alias text of the system font,

00:22:30.140 --> 00:22:30.570
right?

00:22:30.700 --> 00:22:33.780
Carbon, sorry,
Cocoa developers get this for free

00:22:33.780 --> 00:22:35.700
by using the NS Toolbar class.

00:22:35.700 --> 00:22:38.580
They just get this stuff for free,
plus the configuration sheet that

00:22:38.580 --> 00:22:40.020
comes down to configure the toolbar.

00:22:40.200 --> 00:22:42.800
Carbon developers need to
do a little bit more work in

00:22:42.810 --> 00:22:46.370
assembling some of the pieces,
but essentially can easily do this.

00:22:46.680 --> 00:22:50.600
The other thing about these toolbars
is they don't really show status.

00:22:50.600 --> 00:22:53.890
They're used for selecting, you know,
making a choice and moving on.

00:22:54.210 --> 00:22:59.070
And so when you make a choice,
when you select an icon, it darkens 50%.

00:22:59.290 --> 00:23:01.260
So when you look to roll your
own toolbar through Carbon,

00:23:01.340 --> 00:23:05.230
for example, make sure that the icon is
darkened 50%. So if you have

00:23:05.230 --> 00:23:08.330
toolbars in your application,
this is the appearance

00:23:08.330 --> 00:23:09.620
for them on Mac OS X.

