In one of the sessions here, 119,
session 119,

00:24:49.610 --> 00:24:52.920
Carbon Controls and Appearance,
we're going to get into detail as

00:24:52.920 --> 00:24:57.460
to what are the common API changes
that you need to make to get your

00:24:57.460 --> 00:24:59.390
text to draw properly in Mac OS X.

00:25:00.850 --> 00:25:06.900
So one of the great ways of learning is
by looking at pictures of what not to do.

00:25:07.440 --> 00:25:08.800
or what to do.

00:25:08.850 --> 00:25:12.230
And in this case,
because this is just so,

00:25:12.230 --> 00:25:14.180
as we look at applications
that are coming to Mac OS X,

00:25:14.180 --> 00:25:16.740
we're seeing lots of great
examples of what to do.

00:25:16.780 --> 00:25:19.770
We're also seeing lots
of common oversights.

00:25:19.930 --> 00:25:23.690
So rather than fabricate some fake
screenshot that we put together in

00:25:23.730 --> 00:25:28.220
Photoshop to communicate some idea,
I chose to use some real

00:25:28.220 --> 00:25:32.760
developer examples from out there,
maybe some of these are your products,

00:25:32.800 --> 00:25:36.460
and show what some of the common
oversights are with respect

00:25:36.460 --> 00:25:41.370
to creating a great appearance
for your Mac OS X product.

00:25:41.490 --> 00:25:44.240
What are the typical things that
developers are doing today on

00:25:44.240 --> 00:25:44.240
shipping products in Mac OS X?

00:25:44.380 --> 00:25:45.420
So that you can learn from them.

00:25:45.420 --> 00:25:47.880
And this is not an effort
at picking on a developer.

00:25:47.920 --> 00:25:50.490
This is all about
learning from each other.

00:25:51.760 --> 00:25:54.490
First one is wrong window background.

00:25:54.670 --> 00:25:57.240
Windows in Mac OS X come up,
certainly under Carbon,

00:25:57.240 --> 00:25:59.600
by default come up with
a white background.

00:25:59.610 --> 00:26:01.790
So you need to use theme
backgrounds to get the striping,

00:26:01.870 --> 00:26:04.090
the pinstriping background
that's common on Mac OS X.

00:26:04.100 --> 00:26:08.320
So windows on Mac OS X, dialogs,
palettes, utility windows, you know,

00:26:08.320 --> 00:26:12.140
whatever, all the window types have
a pinstripe background.

00:26:12.770 --> 00:26:18.800
Your application needs to have
pinstriping on the background

00:26:18.800 --> 00:26:18.800
of your dialogs in your palette
windows and utility windows.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:23.560
Not only does a white background look,
well basically what this does

00:26:23.560 --> 00:26:25.170
is it makes it look incomplete.

00:26:25.520 --> 00:26:30.390
Aqua controls in fact were designed
to look best on a striped background.

00:26:31.310 --> 00:26:34.960
And using the wrong background,
although this is a really little thing,

00:26:34.960 --> 00:26:37.200
leads to bigger things like this.

00:26:37.250 --> 00:26:39.640
Custom backgrounds,
controls that don't even look.

00:26:39.780 --> 00:26:42.240
This is a Mac OS X product.

00:26:43.130 --> 00:26:45.500
It doesn't even look like Mac OS X.

00:26:45.560 --> 00:26:49.080
It's using not even
Mac OS 9 pop-up menus.

00:26:49.450 --> 00:26:52.950
There's no little down arrow
indicating that those are pop-up menus.

00:26:53.190 --> 00:26:55.560
These look like System 7 pop-up menus.

00:26:55.730 --> 00:26:57.390
Or not even.

00:26:57.570 --> 00:27:01.680
Um, the tabs that are being used,
those three buttons in the top are tabs.

00:27:01.680 --> 00:27:03.090
Non-standard tabs.

00:27:03.230 --> 00:27:05.810
So what this does is it
makes this product feel,

00:27:05.810 --> 00:27:08.500
even though it has
fantastic functionality,

00:27:08.660 --> 00:27:12.210
it makes it feel like it's
not a full class citizen.

00:27:15.630 --> 00:27:20.290
Antialiased text or not,
one of the most common things that we're

00:27:20.290 --> 00:27:23.100
seeing with product shipping-- these
are all shipping products in Mac OS X.

00:27:23.100 --> 00:27:25.590
In fact, this product comes from-- this
dialogue comes from a product

00:27:25.590 --> 00:27:29.720
that's in fact the company's done
a fantastic job moving to 10.

00:27:29.760 --> 00:27:33.360
And yet, in this particular dialogue,
for whatever reason,

00:27:33.610 --> 00:27:37.270
we have a mixture of antialiased
text and non-antialiased text.

00:27:37.280 --> 00:27:40.690
We have a mixture of system font
and hard-coded font references.

00:27:40.790 --> 00:27:44.080
So if you look at the right side of
this screen of this particular dialogue,

00:27:44.160 --> 00:27:46.350
we've got controls that
have the Helvetica font.

00:27:46.700 --> 00:27:49.100
They're not using the system to
draw the font in the controls,

00:27:49.100 --> 00:27:53.450
so they must be drawing the controls
themselves with Appearance Manager maybe,

00:27:53.450 --> 00:27:55.170
but the font is not correct.

00:27:55.270 --> 00:27:58.840
We've got the labels down
the side are Helvetica.

00:27:58.840 --> 00:28:01.790
So we've got Helvetica font on some
controls and on some labels mixed

00:28:01.940 --> 00:28:05.800
with Lucida Grande font that the
system drew on some of the controls.

00:28:05.820 --> 00:28:09.400
If you look, even there's some other
lack of attention to detail.

00:28:09.400 --> 00:28:12.100
Even the baseline of the
text on the labels and the

00:28:12.100 --> 00:28:13.990
controls doesn't even line up.

00:28:14.380 --> 00:28:17.570
So one of the messages I want to
communicate really clearly here

00:28:17.640 --> 00:28:19.940
is that your customers... Hold on,
one of the messages I want to

00:28:20.050 --> 00:28:23.880
communicate here is that you've spent
a lot of time writing your product.

00:28:23.900 --> 00:28:27.280
You've spent a lot of time investing
yourself into the code behind your

00:28:27.280 --> 00:28:30.100
product and all of its functionality.

00:28:30.360 --> 00:28:35.890
If you put on a half-hearted
effort for the user interface,

00:28:36.120 --> 00:28:39.470
people are looking for a fabulous
interface on Mac OS X because it's

00:28:39.470 --> 00:28:41.100
set a new standard for interface.

00:28:41.190 --> 00:28:43.920
If your product doesn't deliver that,
that's how they're going to judge

00:28:43.940 --> 00:28:45.850
the quality of your product.

00:28:45.970 --> 00:28:48.380
And that's highly unfair probably
for the code that you've written,

00:28:48.380 --> 00:28:51.100
because your product probably
does some great stuff.

00:28:51.190 --> 00:28:53.720
But the same way that we buy
cars and we buy other things,

00:28:53.820 --> 00:28:55.530
we look for attention to detail.

00:28:55.710 --> 00:29:00.160
If there's no good icon in your product,
if it's just got a Mac OS 9

00:29:00.160 --> 00:29:04.190
grayscale icon that's scaled
up to 128 by 128 in the dock,

00:29:04.320 --> 00:29:07.470
The first impression
I'm going to have is,

00:29:07.480 --> 00:29:07.480
whoa.

00:29:07.660 --> 00:29:11.100
You know these, wow, they,
looks like they rushed to market.

00:29:11.130 --> 00:29:14.690
And then you get this kind of stuff,
which, which further, you know,

00:29:14.770 --> 00:29:16.740
aggravates that, that idea.

00:29:16.820 --> 00:29:18.380
Or pushes that idea.

00:29:18.600 --> 00:29:20.530
Here's another common mistake.

00:29:20.600 --> 00:29:21.590
Too small text.

00:29:21.700 --> 00:29:23.600
Every developer,
pretty much in this room probably,

00:29:23.600 --> 00:29:28.190
every one of you,
is going to argue that I need to

00:29:28.190 --> 00:29:30.590
use small text in my interface.

00:29:30.680 --> 00:29:32.950
It's got to be really small because
my users want lots of functionality

00:29:32.960 --> 00:29:35.280
on the screen and there's not enough
screen real estate and I've got to

00:29:35.280 --> 00:29:36.600
cram all this stuff on the screen.

00:29:36.600 --> 00:29:39.740
Well, you know what,
that might be the case for some utility

00:29:39.840 --> 00:29:43.500
windows and for pallet windows and
productivity applications that might,

00:29:43.650 --> 00:29:46.600
there's probably some good arguments in
certain instances where that matters.

00:29:46.600 --> 00:29:49.600
And where that's valuable
and where that's important.

00:29:49.850 --> 00:29:52.780
But the vast majority of cases,

00:29:52.910 --> 00:29:55.500
That we see and that
I interact with developers,

00:29:55.520 --> 00:29:59.800
vast majority of cases it's
completely not important to,

00:29:59.800 --> 00:30:01.370
in fact you shouldn't do small text.

00:30:01.370 --> 00:30:02.800
I'm stumbling over my words here.

00:30:02.810 --> 00:30:07.390
The problem with this particular dialogue
for example is this text is so small,

00:30:07.650 --> 00:30:10.800
it's hard to read on a 1024768 display.

00:30:10.820 --> 00:30:13.520
What happens if I start
running this application on

00:30:13.520 --> 00:30:15.650
my new iBook that has 160 P.I.

00:30:15.690 --> 00:30:16.540
running Mac OS X?

00:30:16.660 --> 00:30:19.610
I can't read it.

00:30:19.950 --> 00:30:23.360
So be very careful where
you choose small text.

00:30:23.390 --> 00:30:28.110
Dialog boxes like this one
are transient in nature.

00:30:28.150 --> 00:30:30.550
You display a dialog because the
user told you to display the dialog.

00:30:30.600 --> 00:30:31.680
They chose something in the interface.

00:30:31.680 --> 00:30:32.860
A dialog appears.

00:30:32.880 --> 00:30:33.910
It could be much bigger.

00:30:33.970 --> 00:30:38.620
This dialog could grow 25% or 30%
and use the full-size system font,

00:30:38.620 --> 00:30:43.840
large system font, everywhere on it,
and it would be equally usable.

00:30:43.970 --> 00:30:46.300
And because dialogues are transient,
they can be much bigger.

00:30:46.300 --> 00:30:47.560
You can use standard-sized controls.

00:30:47.660 --> 00:30:49.880
You can use standard-sized text,
large system font.

00:30:49.910 --> 00:30:53.090
Because I'm focused in that as a user,
I'm not interacting with other

00:30:53.090 --> 00:30:55.140
stuff on my screen typically.

00:30:55.190 --> 00:30:57.850
Careful how often you use small text.

00:30:58.740 --> 00:31:00.590
Another common problem:
mixing small and large text.

00:31:00.770 --> 00:31:02.600
Here we've got a dialogue,
or a portion of a dialogue,

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:06.330
that's got standard font
in the pop-up menus,

00:31:06.470 --> 00:31:11.050
but it's got small system
font for the labels.

00:31:13.140 --> 00:31:17.180
If you're using small controls,
then use small labels.

00:31:17.180 --> 00:31:22.100
If you're using large controls,
standard controls, use large system font.

00:31:22.100 --> 00:31:24.460
Because what this does
is it looks incomplete.

00:31:24.520 --> 00:31:25.390
It looks unfinished.

00:31:28.120 --> 00:31:29.440
There's another thing.

00:31:29.450 --> 00:31:30.300
It might be a list.

00:31:30.410 --> 00:31:32.000
I'm not sure what this is.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:35.420
In fact, lists on Mac OS X have
a white background.

00:31:35.530 --> 00:31:36.990
This one's got a striped background.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:41.000
This list is using non-standard
font for the contents of the list.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:43.000
So it's a Helvetic or something.

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:45.000
I'm not even sure what it is.

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:47.850
The OK and Cancel are in the right place,
but we're going to get to that shortly.

00:31:47.970 --> 00:31:52.000
And along the top here we have,
what are they, white bevel buttons?

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:53.920
Oh, they're column headers.

00:31:53.920 --> 00:31:58.000
Well, on Mac OS X, there's a particular
appearance for list headers.

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:01.450
For Carbon, if you use Data Browser APIs,
the Data Browser will give you the right

00:32:01.450 --> 00:32:03.000
appearance in Mac OS 9 and on Mac OS X.

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:05.540
It just does the right thing
for column headers and it takes

00:32:05.690 --> 00:32:08.890
care of a lot of other stuff,
like cool animation of columns

00:32:08.890 --> 00:32:10.550
as you move them around.

00:32:10.740 --> 00:32:13.720
It does the right thing for you,
saving you, helping you,

00:32:13.720 --> 00:32:16.590
or allowing you to focus on
the value add for your product

00:32:16.590 --> 00:32:18.300
and letting us do the UI code.

00:32:18.300 --> 00:32:21.750
And in Cocoa,
lists can be done with NSOutlineView and

00:32:21.800 --> 00:32:26.190
NSBrowserView and some of the
other classes that are available.

00:32:26.290 --> 00:32:30.600
So lists have a white background,
the dialogue has a striped background.

00:32:34.820 --> 00:32:36.560
This is common.

00:32:36.560 --> 00:32:40.310
And that is where we have a
duality in character for controls.

00:32:40.430 --> 00:32:43.230
And the most common of these is
button labels or label buttons

00:32:43.290 --> 00:32:45.400
or... I'm not sure which it is.

00:32:45.530 --> 00:32:48.170
So as I look at this dialog,
it's laid out great.

00:32:48.280 --> 00:32:50.610
It's followed the interface, you know,
the layout guidelines,

00:32:50.610 --> 00:32:51.980
the spacing and stuff like that.

00:32:52.100 --> 00:32:54.660
It's got full Aqua, you know,
the right pinstriping,

00:32:54.660 --> 00:32:57.290
got the right controls,
everything like that.

00:32:57.290 --> 00:32:57.290
The problem is...

00:32:57.770 --> 00:33:00.180
Is gradation a button?

00:33:00.180 --> 00:33:02.600
Or is it a label for the
pop-up menu beside it?

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:05.340
Well, it's both, actually.

00:33:05.850 --> 00:33:08.980
For people who are used to the computer,
they could probably figure this out,

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:10.000
and it's not that big a deal.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:12.580
We probably wouldn't even think,
you know, very much about this.

00:33:12.700 --> 00:33:16.900
But for new users, new customers,
it's confusing.

00:33:16.940 --> 00:33:19.670
A button is not a label.

00:33:19.720 --> 00:33:20.640
A button is a button.

00:33:20.920 --> 00:33:23.240
A pop-up menu needs a label.

00:33:23.280 --> 00:33:28.240
Interface elements were
designed for specific reasons.

00:33:28.240 --> 00:33:31.270
Use them for what they were designed for,
and don't make them do

00:33:31.270 --> 00:33:31.270
two different things.

00:33:35.030 --> 00:33:36.950
Going back to a dialogue that we
looked at a little bit before in

00:33:37.060 --> 00:33:40.440
terms of the font size mixing up,
something else I want to bring

00:33:40.440 --> 00:33:42.790
attention to is something else
I see fairly often in products

00:33:42.790 --> 00:33:45.810
that are shipping on 10 today,
and that is this button

00:33:45.810 --> 00:33:47.700
that has an ellipsis in it.

00:33:47.730 --> 00:33:48.880
What does it do?

00:33:48.900 --> 00:33:50.380
I don't know.

00:33:52.530 --> 00:33:55.760
What they really want this to do
is essentially be the last item in

00:33:55.760 --> 00:33:59.400
those pop-up menus where there's a
separator that says more or other.

00:33:59.400 --> 00:34:00.380
Right?

00:34:00.430 --> 00:34:02.450
Maybe it's a font list or,
well in this case I forget

00:34:02.450 --> 00:34:05.400
what's in these menus,
but maybe it's a list of font sizes

00:34:05.400 --> 00:34:09.570
and then there's a separator spacing,
right, and then it says other,

00:34:09.570 --> 00:34:10.760
dot dot dot.

00:34:11.290 --> 00:34:14.230
So unless something has to be
elevated to the primary level,

00:34:14.230 --> 00:34:16.330
you know,
to the highest level in the interface,

00:34:16.330 --> 00:34:19.520
a dot dot dot button is not something
that users are going to understand.

00:34:19.520 --> 00:34:22.540
And the problem here is that it cuts down
on productivity because the user has to

00:34:22.540 --> 00:34:24.030
click on this thing to see what it does.

00:34:24.080 --> 00:34:25.200
Oh, okay.

00:34:25.200 --> 00:34:29.500
And then they make a mental note about
what this does and hopefully they

00:34:29.500 --> 00:34:29.500
remember what it does in the future.

00:34:32.270 --> 00:34:33.900
Too many group boxes.

00:34:33.930 --> 00:34:38.450
One of the design goals in Aqua was to
eliminate black lines and hard edges and

00:34:38.560 --> 00:34:43.600
move to a softer environment that has
lots of breathing space and white space,

00:34:43.630 --> 00:34:45.160
and that sort of thing.

00:34:45.180 --> 00:34:48.140
And this is a fantastic
product on Mac OS X.

00:34:48.140 --> 00:34:52.240
They've done a fabulous job with this
from a technological point of view.

00:34:52.270 --> 00:34:55.240
But here's a great example of
a dialogue box that has way

00:34:55.240 --> 00:34:57.280
too many group boxes in it.

00:34:57.310 --> 00:34:59.950
And in fact, the goal for the developer,
probably,

00:35:00.140 --> 00:35:05.000
was to make the group boxes help the
user navigate the dialogue and find

00:35:05.050 --> 00:35:07.780
the things that they're looking for.

00:35:08.140 --> 00:35:09.590
But in fact,
they've not accomplished that.

00:35:09.690 --> 00:35:11.920
They've gone,
it's in fact done the wrong thing.

00:35:11.920 --> 00:35:12.740
It's gone the other way.

00:35:12.740 --> 00:35:16.230
In fact, all the lines now make it
very confusing to read.

00:35:16.370 --> 00:35:19.940
And we're going to get into some examples
later of how to avoid using group

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:23.940
boxes but use separator lines and white
spacing to accomplish the same goal.

00:35:24.080 --> 00:35:25.890
And yet it makes the
dialogue far more readable.

00:35:25.940 --> 00:35:31.030
If you do have to use group boxes,
which are available in Aqua,

00:35:31.130 --> 00:35:34.170
there's a primary group box and
there's a secondary group box,

00:35:34.170 --> 00:35:35.540
which have both different appearances.

00:35:35.540 --> 00:35:38.000
So in the case where you might
have a group box within another

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:40.520
one where it's warranted,
there's another appearance

00:35:40.520 --> 00:35:41.470
for a secondary group box.

00:35:41.550 --> 00:35:44.570
So look in the interface
guidelines for details on that.

