00:37:40.850 --> 00:37:43.810
Toolbar overdose.

00:37:43.870 --> 00:37:46.400
This is actually a real
product shipping on 10.

00:37:46.660 --> 00:37:49.240
And when you fire it up
for the very first time,

00:37:49.270 --> 00:37:51.310
you get-- well,
I think it's nine toolbars

00:37:51.470 --> 00:37:53.660
showing up on screen.

00:37:53.660 --> 00:37:59.030
And not only that-- well, first of all,
what that shows me is that the

00:37:59.260 --> 00:38:02.160
programmer or the programmers or
whatever felt that every single

00:38:02.370 --> 00:38:05.230
piece of code that they wrote was
extremely important and needed to be

00:38:05.230 --> 00:38:06.820
connected up to an interface element.

00:38:06.890 --> 00:38:10.080
Because they wanted the user
to use that cool feature.

00:38:10.120 --> 00:38:12.420
That's not what usability is about.

00:38:12.440 --> 00:38:16.130
Usability is about progressive
disclosure to your users to allow them

00:38:16.130 --> 00:38:19.720
to move through the process of solving
a problem that they're trying to solve,

00:38:19.750 --> 00:38:22.320
and you providing a great
solution for your software.

00:38:22.330 --> 00:38:25.800
Don't just expose every feature in
your application to the interface.

00:38:25.810 --> 00:38:29.780
Don't populate the menus with
every possible hook into your code.

00:38:29.800 --> 00:38:32.130
It just makes for a completely
confusing environment.

00:38:32.270 --> 00:38:36.190
This is synonymous with taking
every control in an automobile and

00:38:36.190 --> 00:38:38.290
putting it on the steering wheel.

00:38:39.060 --> 00:38:40.100
It becomes highly unusable.

00:38:40.100 --> 00:38:41.000
You can't find anything.

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:42.060
How would you possibly drive?

00:38:42.140 --> 00:38:44.180
How would you do stuff?

00:38:44.640 --> 00:38:47.160
Not only that,
but we have appearance issues here.

00:38:47.160 --> 00:38:49.290
It doesn't look like a Mac OS X toolbar,
right?

00:38:49.300 --> 00:38:51.060
We talked about the toolbar
design for Mac OS X.

00:38:51.060 --> 00:38:55.500
It's clean, straight background,
nice icons up on a background,

00:38:55.500 --> 00:38:57.740
although this is the bevel button,
which is another option.

00:38:57.740 --> 00:38:58.300
That's true.

00:38:58.300 --> 00:39:01.000
But we have the font inside
of some of the controls here

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:02.500
is Helvetica or something.

00:39:02.500 --> 00:39:03.540
It's not Lucida.

00:39:03.540 --> 00:39:06.340
We have a pop-up menu at
the top for percentage,

00:39:06.340 --> 00:39:09.260
which looks like it's
trying to be a combo box,

00:39:09.370 --> 00:39:11.020
but it's a pop-up,
but it's an edit field.

00:39:11.020 --> 00:39:14.660
So we've got this multi-characteristic
schizophrenic control,

00:39:14.810 --> 00:39:17.650
which really becomes
highly confusing for users.

00:39:17.770 --> 00:39:19.500
And why is it confusing?

00:39:19.800 --> 00:39:21.930
Because it doesn't look like
anything they're used to.

00:39:22.030 --> 00:39:23.600
It kind of looks like
something they're used to,

00:39:23.600 --> 00:39:24.710
so maybe they'll figure it out.

00:39:24.710 --> 00:39:29.490
But it doesn't lend users to
self-confidence and to encourage them

00:39:29.570 --> 00:39:32.110
to move on and learn the product.

00:39:33.080 --> 00:39:36.240
Step 5 about being a good
citizen is layout guidelines.

00:39:36.270 --> 00:39:40.760
We publish very detailed
information about the spacing

00:39:40.760 --> 00:39:43.040
between interface elements.

00:39:43.360 --> 00:39:46.540
And we've thought long and hard
about why this is important.

00:39:46.590 --> 00:39:48.240
It comes down to readability.

00:39:48.240 --> 00:39:52.290
It comes down to navigation
of content of your dialogues.

00:39:52.330 --> 00:39:54.270
It comes down to localization issues.

00:39:54.280 --> 00:39:56.740
It comes down to the overall
appearance of Mac OS X.

00:39:56.740 --> 00:40:00.020
Lots of white space and
breathing room and a light,

00:40:00.380 --> 00:40:02.860
friendly,
kind of lively feeling to Mac OS X.

00:40:03.250 --> 00:40:05.000
So it's important to follow these.

00:40:05.070 --> 00:40:07.520
And we're not suggesting
that you memorize this stuff,

00:40:07.520 --> 00:40:10.190
because we've got a great
tool that's available that

00:40:10.190 --> 00:40:13.530
you've seen already probably,
called Interface Builder that lets

00:40:13.650 --> 00:40:17.440
you basically draw your interface,
drag and drop elements on screen,

00:40:17.500 --> 00:40:19.970
and as you drag these things on screen,
you get guidelines that sort

00:40:19.970 --> 00:40:22.980
of snap in place that say,
"Hey, this is the right place for that,"

00:40:23.030 --> 00:40:25.900
with respect to that other control
or with respect to the edge of the

00:40:25.900 --> 00:40:27.740
window or the tab panel or whatever.

00:40:27.790 --> 00:40:31.490
Interface Builder is a
fantastic prototyping tool.

00:40:31.800 --> 00:40:36.190
Not only does it let you draw this stuff,
but it lets you hook it up to code.

00:40:36.250 --> 00:40:38.980
And you saw in the keynote address
where Scott Forstall demonstrated this.

00:40:39.160 --> 00:40:41.490
Fantastic example of
how this is a really,

00:40:41.590 --> 00:40:43.660
this is a prototyper with a kick.

00:40:44.610 --> 00:40:47.440
It's the UI design tool of choice
and we're going to continue

00:40:47.680 --> 00:40:50.840
to extend this tool so that it
becomes the premier design tool

00:40:50.840 --> 00:40:53.380
for interface design at Apple.

00:40:54.550 --> 00:41:06.970
Carbon APIs are available to,
this is not only just

00:41:06.970 --> 00:41:06.970
for Cocoa developers.

00:41:06.970 --> 00:41:06.970
Carbon developers can use the
output from Interface Builder

00:41:06.970 --> 00:41:06.970
and extract the resources in
the windows that are in there.

00:41:06.970 --> 00:41:06.970
Those APIs exist and we're
going to talk about those in

00:41:06.970 --> 00:41:06.970
some of the other sessions.

00:41:07.360 --> 00:41:11.850
So let's look at some common scenarios
that we're seeing as products

00:41:11.850 --> 00:41:14.770
come to Mac OS X of developers
who are not adopting the interface

00:41:14.890 --> 00:41:17.190
guidelines in terms of layout,
you know, guidelines.

00:41:17.200 --> 00:41:19.880
And we're going to look at why
this matters and how you can

00:41:19.880 --> 00:41:23.620
transition a dialogue that doesn't
follow this stuff into a dialogue

00:41:23.620 --> 00:41:28.510
that does and how dramatically
it affects the overall usability.

00:41:30.640 --> 00:41:33.700
Here's a preference panel from an
application that's available on 10 today.

00:41:33.770 --> 00:41:36.780
Fantastic application.

