And the dramatic effect
that you see here,

00:42:15.650 --> 00:42:19.120
if that is applied to every single
dialog box in your application,

00:42:19.120 --> 00:42:23.880
every single palette window or utility
window or whatever you want to call them,

00:42:23.980 --> 00:42:29.260
but if you take these guidelines
and apply them to your application,

00:42:29.260 --> 00:42:34.720
you could ship that application
simply by applying the guidelines and

00:42:34.720 --> 00:42:35.150
people would buy it because it looks
so much better and it's so much more

00:42:35.150 --> 00:42:35.150
navigatable and so much more usable.

00:42:35.370 --> 00:42:37.980
So the effect on your
application moving to Mac OS X,

00:42:37.990 --> 00:42:40.300
applying these guidelines is dramatic.

00:42:40.300 --> 00:42:43.430
We've seen developers who have
taken the time to do this and

00:42:43.430 --> 00:42:45.420
they're blown away by the results.

00:42:45.420 --> 00:42:48.070
Their quality assurance teams
look at these things and go,

00:42:48.070 --> 00:42:51.180
"Wow, this is great." And yet the
developers haven't done anything.

00:42:51.180 --> 00:42:53.720
They've only modified the
layout guidelines or the

00:42:53.720 --> 00:42:55.260
layout of their dialogues.

00:42:55.300 --> 00:42:56.260
Here's another example.

00:42:56.260 --> 00:42:58.420
This is a shipping product on Mac OS X.

00:42:58.420 --> 00:43:00.200
We've got a bunch of problems here.

00:43:00.270 --> 00:43:02.400
We've got check boxes way
too close to each other,

00:43:02.400 --> 00:43:05.970
although they're on a white list,
so we'll give them credit for that.

00:43:06.040 --> 00:43:10.660
We've got some big buttons on the right,
which we're not sure what they do,

00:43:10.660 --> 00:43:12.660
but we'll talk about that in a second.

00:43:12.860 --> 00:43:16.760
And then we've got some text at the top,
which is the list label, I guess,

00:43:16.790 --> 00:43:18.680
but the text is clipped.

00:43:18.780 --> 00:43:20.320
It's cut off.

00:43:20.320 --> 00:43:22.590
This is shipping on 10.

00:43:23.100 --> 00:43:24.700
So what does that say to you as a user?

00:43:24.700 --> 00:43:27.080
If you buy a product,
you spend 200 bucks or whatever

00:43:27.080 --> 00:43:29.930
you spend on the product,
and you fire this thing up and

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:31.830
there's text that's cut off.

00:43:32.690 --> 00:43:35.100
The effect it has on you is that
you have an immediate impression

00:43:35.180 --> 00:43:37.920
and you make a decision,
you form an opinion about the

00:43:37.990 --> 00:43:40.900
quality of that product based on
what you're seeing in the interface,

00:43:40.900 --> 00:43:42.600
and you maybe haven't even
done anything with the product.

00:43:42.630 --> 00:43:44.950
Maybe it does provide a great solution.

00:43:45.240 --> 00:43:48.600
Maybe it does have highly
functional characteristics.

00:43:48.640 --> 00:43:51.100
And yet you make a decision about
its quality based on the interface.

00:43:51.100 --> 00:43:53.500
So for all of you out
there who are writing code,

00:43:53.620 --> 00:43:56.180
if you're not one of the
UI designers at your company,

00:43:56.380 --> 00:43:59.020
get on the UI designers to make
sure that they do a good job

00:43:59.120 --> 00:44:02.600
because otherwise your code will
be misrepresented to your users.

00:44:04.160 --> 00:44:06.980
So when you apply the layout guidelines,
not only do you adjust the spacing

00:44:06.980 --> 00:44:11.060
and get rid of the clipping text,
but you end up thinking about

00:44:11.200 --> 00:44:12.220
the overall functionality.

00:44:12.300 --> 00:44:14.200
Does this need to be a modal dialog?

00:44:14.210 --> 00:44:17.080
In fact, if we make it a modalist dialog,
we can simplify the dialog

00:44:17.080 --> 00:44:18.670
and make it a lot cleaner.

00:44:18.760 --> 00:44:20.560
So we end up with this.

00:44:20.630 --> 00:44:22.100
Check all, uncheck all.

00:44:22.160 --> 00:44:24.950
Turns on and off all of the
check boxes in the list.

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:27.860
We've had the spacing list,
put the right font at the top.

00:44:27.910 --> 00:44:31.550
Dramatic change from this to this.

00:44:31.820 --> 00:44:34.750
If you apply the layout guidelines
using Interface Builder or

00:44:34.760 --> 00:44:38.590
whatever tool you want to use,
you get dramatic effects in your product.

00:44:38.600 --> 00:44:42.140
Dramatic usability increases,
productivity increases.

00:44:42.260 --> 00:44:46.800
So the cumulative effect of a
lot of these oversights is an

00:44:46.800 --> 00:44:48.860
interface that's very confusing.

00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:52.220
Here's an example of a
product shipping on Mac OS X.

00:44:52.310 --> 00:44:55.000
It's a great product, it really is.

00:44:55.200 --> 00:44:58.770
But it's hindered by a
really clumsy interface.

00:44:58.990 --> 00:45:04.300
We've got label buttons or
button labels at the top.

00:45:04.300 --> 00:45:09.690
We've got features that are
just sort of existing in space.

00:45:09.690 --> 00:45:12.780
I don't know why we have a checkbox
