00:46:37.650 --> 00:46:38.200
okay?

00:46:38.240 --> 00:46:41.850
And we see that a lot.

00:46:42.190 --> 00:46:44.370
And this is not to pick
on this developer at all.

00:46:44.370 --> 00:46:44.370
I see that a lot.

00:46:45.200 --> 00:46:47.180
So when you apply the
layout guidelines to this,

00:46:47.180 --> 00:46:51.890
you end up with something that's
highly more navigatable visually.

00:46:52.190 --> 00:46:56.490
There are visual cues, there's groupings,
dramatic change.

00:46:58.650 --> 00:47:03.300
Tab along the top, labels and pop-ups,
you don't have duality

00:47:03.300 --> 00:47:04.740
of meanings and controls.

00:47:04.840 --> 00:47:09.400
You've got groupings, original image,
scanned image, image quality, you know,

00:47:09.500 --> 00:47:13.130
the center alignment of sort of
center orientation of stuff in Aqua,

00:47:13.190 --> 00:47:16.210
great white spacing,
the proper help button,

00:47:16.210 --> 00:47:19.200
no more closed box, all that stuff.

00:47:20.460 --> 00:47:25.220
Big difference in usability
between that and that.

00:47:25.360 --> 00:47:28.500
So it does matter to apply this stuff.

00:47:28.550 --> 00:47:30.530
And I interact with a
lot of developers who go,

00:47:30.540 --> 00:47:30.920
oh yeah.

00:47:31.150 --> 00:47:33.600
You know, what does it matter?

00:47:33.660 --> 00:47:34.910
Well it really does.

00:47:35.210 --> 00:47:38.000
Because we see lots of examples
as we interact with you,

00:47:38.000 --> 00:47:40.760
looking at your products on 10,
and it affects the usability.

00:47:40.760 --> 00:47:44.310
It affects the self-confidence of users.

00:47:44.320 --> 00:47:45.560
It affects their productivity.

00:47:45.560 --> 00:47:48.240
It affects all those things that
we talked about at the beginning

00:47:48.260 --> 00:47:51.780
that ultimately user benefits
roll into developer benefits.

00:47:51.820 --> 00:47:56.080
You want to make money on Mac OS X,
make a product that is so easy to use,

00:47:56.140 --> 00:47:59.480
and so navigatable,
and so visually gorgeous like this,

00:47:59.500 --> 00:48:02.080
you will make money on Mac OS X.

00:48:02.080 --> 00:48:06.170
It's not about just bringing your
code to Mac OS X and making it native.

00:48:06.190 --> 00:48:07.900
Because that just gets
you to the platform,

00:48:07.900 --> 00:48:08.520
remember?

00:48:08.520 --> 00:48:11.400
It doesn't get you on the platform.

00:48:11.880 --> 00:48:13.210
So don't be a stranger in a strange land.

00:48:13.300 --> 00:48:14.720
I've talked about this message a lot.

00:48:14.720 --> 00:48:16.620
I'm not going to carry
on about that more.

00:48:16.620 --> 00:48:19.120
Let's talk about the new layout
in terms of the layout guidelines.

00:48:19.120 --> 00:48:22.460
This is a little bit different,
but there's a new layout

00:48:22.590 --> 00:48:24.480
in Mac OS X for menus.

00:48:24.480 --> 00:48:26.730
And this came about, again,
to try to solve a problem,

00:48:26.790 --> 00:48:31.780
an age-old problem that we've had on
the Mac whereby we've become so used

00:48:31.860 --> 00:48:35.630
to-- certainly those in the audience who
are from the Macintosh background-- have

00:48:35.630 --> 00:48:40.460
become so used to quitting an application
by going to the File menu Quit.

00:48:40.460 --> 00:48:44.690
They haven't even thought about the fact
that that makes absolutely no sense.

00:48:44.910 --> 00:48:47.180
We don't quit files.

00:48:47.200 --> 00:48:49.160
You quit applications.

00:48:49.180 --> 00:48:50.150
You close files.

00:48:50.300 --> 00:48:51.140
You save files.

00:48:51.250 --> 00:48:52.080
You print files.

00:48:52.090 --> 00:48:52.700
You open them.

00:48:52.810 --> 00:48:54.740
But you don't quit them.

00:48:54.740 --> 00:48:58.070
Although that's a term that people say,
I'm going to quit this document.

00:48:58.320 --> 00:48:59.490
But that's a misuse of the term.

00:48:59.620 --> 00:49:01.360
We quit applications.

00:49:01.390 --> 00:49:04.780
And so we've taken the opportunity
in Aqua to introduce a new hierarchy

00:49:04.780 --> 00:49:08.130
in the menu bar that starts on
the left with the Apple menu,

00:49:08.130 --> 00:49:09.640
which is system global.

00:49:09.670 --> 00:49:12.620
This menu shouldn't be populated by you.

00:49:12.640 --> 00:49:16.980
This is not for developer features,
developer commands.

00:49:17.150 --> 00:49:18.560
This is for the system.

00:49:18.580 --> 00:49:21.820
And the new Apple menu is
accessible everywhere in the system,

00:49:21.820 --> 00:49:23.400
regardless of what application you're in.

00:49:23.400 --> 00:49:25.650
You can get the same
functionality in the Apple menu,

00:49:26.110 --> 00:49:28.970
unlike what you could do in Mac OS 9,
which was highly frustrating.

00:49:28.980 --> 00:49:32.020
Now that once you see the new design,
you go back to Mac OS 9, it's like, ah,

00:49:32.050 --> 00:49:32.400
blast.

00:49:32.400 --> 00:49:35.520
I've got to click on Finder and then go
to the Apple menu to find about this Mac.

00:49:35.530 --> 00:49:37.000
In Mac OS X,
you just go to the Apple menu, boom,

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:38.660
about this Macintosh.

00:49:38.680 --> 00:49:39.880
Or this computer, whatever it says.

00:49:42.720 --> 00:49:44.500
The next one, moving right.

00:49:44.520 --> 00:49:46.260
First one is the Apple menu,
system global.

00:49:46.260 --> 00:49:48.540
Now we have application global.

00:49:48.590 --> 00:49:50.900
So the things that you put in
the application global menu are

00:49:50.900 --> 00:49:53.470
the things that relate to your
application on a global scale,

00:49:53.700 --> 00:49:54.940
like preferences.

00:49:54.940 --> 00:49:57.520
An application has preferences.

00:49:57.530 --> 00:49:59.200
Sometimes documents have preferences.

00:49:59.200 --> 00:50:01.380
And what we're encouraging you through
the interface guidelines is to put

00:50:01.380 --> 00:50:05.220
a preference item in the application
menu that is hierarchical in nature,

00:50:05.220 --> 00:50:09.340
that says preferences, application,
preferences document.

00:50:09.550 --> 00:50:12.040
But in most cases,
applications have preferences and they

00:50:12.170 --> 00:50:13.550
should go in the application menu.

00:50:13.550 --> 00:50:15.800
And therefore,
with the application menu in place,

00:50:15.800 --> 00:50:17.660
we now have a great place
to put the quit item,

00:50:17.890 --> 00:50:18.040
right?

00:50:18.150 --> 00:50:19.900
We quit processes on X.

00:50:19.900 --> 00:50:21.240
We quit applications.

00:50:21.390 --> 00:50:23.400
That's where the quit menu should go.

00:50:23.500 --> 00:50:26.690
So as you move from Mac OS 9 to Mac OS X,
one of the first things you need to do

00:50:26.690 --> 00:50:30.150
is make sure that your menu structure
adheres to the Mac OS X menu structure.

00:50:30.630 --> 00:50:33.310
Move your preferences item
from wherever it was before.

00:50:33.390 --> 00:50:35.730
In many cases, it's the edit menu,
but in many cases,

00:50:35.780 --> 00:50:38.400
it's elsewhere and it's not
even called preferences.

00:50:38.570 --> 00:50:41.590
Call it preferences and put
it in the application menu.

00:50:44.510 --> 00:50:48.840
Moving right, we have the File menu,
which is document global, in a sense,

00:50:48.940 --> 00:50:50.280
document centric.

00:50:50.280 --> 00:50:52.740
So you put into the File menu
the things that relate to

00:50:52.820 --> 00:50:54.400
your application documents.

00:50:54.460 --> 00:50:57.150
Saving, opening, printing, page setup.

00:50:57.150 --> 00:51:00.380
You actually close,
we put the Close one in here.

00:51:00.400 --> 00:51:02.450
We didn't put it in the Window menu,
we put it in the File menu

00:51:02.450 --> 00:51:03.860
because you actually close files.

00:51:03.910 --> 00:51:07.020
And a lot of people think of it that way,
and so that's where the Close command is.

00:51:08.140 --> 00:51:10.460
The Window menu is really
for manipulating windows and

00:51:10.460 --> 00:51:13.260
tiling them and arranging them,
but this is where we put Close.

00:51:13.370 --> 00:51:16.390
So pay attention to that too.

00:51:16.390 --> 00:51:16.390
Some people overlook that.

00:51:17.610 --> 00:51:19.100
Next, moving right again.

00:51:19.200 --> 00:51:21.370
So we've got, so starting at the left,
just to remind you, right?

00:51:21.560 --> 00:51:24.840
System global, app global,
document specific.

00:51:25.200 --> 00:51:27.990
Now we're looking at
document content specific.

00:51:27.990 --> 00:51:30.300
So the next menus are all
about document content.

00:51:30.490 --> 00:51:36.120
And then you've got the window
and help menu at the end.

00:51:37.620 --> 00:51:39.810
For the system, which the system takes
care of in many cases,

00:51:39.810 --> 00:51:42.640
and the help menu is where you're
going to hook up your user assistance.

00:51:42.720 --> 00:51:46.170
Remember we talked about how a good
application delivers help through,

00:51:46.300 --> 00:51:47.450
delivers user assistance?

00:51:47.720 --> 00:51:51.490
This is where you would hook up your user
assistance for Apple help on Mac OS X.

00:51:53.120 --> 00:51:54.310
Predefine file locations.

00:51:54.320 --> 00:51:58.090
On Mac OS X, every user has an account,
right?

00:51:58.100 --> 00:52:02.260
And in that account, in that setup,
they've got a default directory,

00:52:02.360 --> 00:52:07.840
a predefined directory for movies,
for documents, for music, for pictures.

00:52:07.840 --> 00:52:12.000
So don't put your application
support files in the music folder.

00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:14.580
Put them in the library folder
in a folder that's titled

00:52:14.580 --> 00:52:15.480
according to your application.

00:52:15.500 --> 00:52:18.580
If you save music,
make the default location

00:52:18.580 --> 00:52:20.620
the user's music directory.

00:52:20.620 --> 00:52:24.070
And after that,
if the user chooses to make another place

00:52:24.070 --> 00:52:26.060
for you to save as a default location,
fine.

00:52:26.060 --> 00:52:27.640
But that's the user's choice.

00:52:29.040 --> 00:52:32.120
But a well-behaved application of
Mac OS X that delivers a great user

00:52:32.300 --> 00:52:36.140
experience is going to respect the
default predefined file locations

00:52:36.140 --> 00:52:38.880
that are available on per user basis.

00:52:40.090 --> 00:52:42.130
And the new interface guidelines,
by the way, they're published today

00:52:42.130 --> 00:52:46.860
and available on the web,
talk about when you should

00:52:46.980 --> 00:52:52.150
use those locations,
what they are,

00:52:52.150 --> 00:52:52.150
and when they're to be used,
and that sort of thing.

00:52:52.150 --> 00:52:52.150
Another building block of a great
user experience on 10 is Apple Help.

00:52:57.100 --> 00:52:59.090
Apple Help is a lightweight HTML browser.

00:52:59.090 --> 00:53:02.140
Basically,
we've been talking about this for

00:53:02.140 --> 00:53:06.040
two years and it's not a memory hog.

00:53:06.090 --> 00:53:06.920
It's there.

00:53:07.100 --> 00:53:10.100
It's written in a way specifically
to deliver quick content,

00:53:10.100 --> 00:53:11.490
feature-rich content.

00:53:11.500 --> 00:53:13.200
You can put QuickTime movies
and sound in there.

00:53:13.200 --> 00:53:16.780
We've got a great announcement to
make in the Apple Help session on,

00:53:16.850 --> 00:53:19.440
I forget which day it is, session 125.

00:53:19.460 --> 00:53:20.900
Anyway, I think it's Thursday or
it might be today.

00:53:20.900 --> 00:53:21.200
I'm not sure.

00:53:21.200 --> 00:53:21.900
Look on your calendar.

00:53:21.960 --> 00:53:24.850
But session 125,
we've got a great announcement

00:53:24.850 --> 00:53:28.800
about moving some content from other
platforms into Apple Help format.

00:53:28.830 --> 00:53:31.720
But Apple Help is the way you
should deliver user assistance.

00:53:31.750 --> 00:53:34.100
We're going to be extending
Apple Help functionality in the future,

00:53:34.100 --> 00:53:36.560
of course, as we're going to extend
everything in the operating system.

00:53:36.660 --> 00:53:41.350
But this is where and how you should
deliver user assistance on Mac OS X.

00:53:41.380 --> 00:53:43.440
It's going to provide
an anti-aliased display.

00:53:43.440 --> 00:53:45.180
It's going to provide
really rich content.

00:53:45.210 --> 00:53:45.990
Do it this way.

00:53:46.250 --> 00:53:47.440
Don't roll your own.

00:53:47.460 --> 00:53:50.570
Let us deliver the services that are
user experience related wherever we

00:53:50.670 --> 00:53:51.940
can so that you can focus on the things
that are going to be used in the future.

00:53:51.950 --> 00:53:54.820
Don't just focus on the solutions that
you need to be providing to your users.

00:53:55.020 --> 00:53:57.180
Don't spend time writing a help viewer.

00:53:57.230 --> 00:53:58.780
We already did that.

00:53:58.780 --> 00:54:02.500
And if it doesn't have the functionality
that you're interested in or that

00:54:02.500 --> 00:54:05.770
you need for a particular case,
work with me and develop relations

00:54:05.890 --> 00:54:07.690
to get that functionality added.

00:54:08.480 --> 00:54:10.700
Talk about that in a little
bit of detail later on.

00:54:10.760 --> 00:54:12.000
The new window layering model.

00:54:12.070 --> 00:54:14.490
Here's another example of where
in Aqua we're trying to go beyond

00:54:14.490 --> 00:54:16.600
the experience that we've had
before and solve some of the

00:54:16.690 --> 00:54:18.200
problems we've had in the past.

00:54:18.250 --> 00:54:20.640
In Mac OS 9,
when you have multiple applications open

00:54:20.640 --> 00:54:24.040
with multiple document windows open,
it becomes really confusing and

00:54:24.040 --> 00:54:29.140
frustrating sometimes to move data from a
Finder window into an application window.

00:54:29.190 --> 00:54:31.230
Because every time you
click on one of the,

00:54:31.240 --> 00:54:33.000
you know,
whether you click on Finder or the app,

00:54:33.050 --> 00:54:38.860
all of the windows come forward from
that application and maintain their,

00:54:39.760 --> 00:54:41.240
Z order.

00:54:41.240 --> 00:54:43.890
As a Canadian, I would say Z order.

00:54:43.940 --> 00:54:45.660
But they maintain the
ordering that's there,

00:54:45.660 --> 00:54:47.300
that the user put in place.

00:54:47.300 --> 00:54:50.320
And that becomes really
frustrating for moving data back

00:54:50.420 --> 00:54:52.640
and forth through drag and drop,
for example.

00:54:52.640 --> 00:54:56.190
So one of our design goals with Aqua was
to enhance that functionality and solve

00:54:56.190 --> 00:55:00.200
some of the usability issues there,
create a more modeless environment

00:55:00.200 --> 00:55:01.910
that'll support Sheets,
which we're going to

00:55:01.910 --> 00:55:04.970
talk about in a second,
but have this interleaved document model,

00:55:04.980 --> 00:55:08.540
which allows you to have multiple
applications open with multiple documents

00:55:08.800 --> 00:55:13.480
and interleave an Excel window with
a MetroWorks window with a WordPro,

00:55:13.480 --> 00:55:14.300
whatever.

00:55:14.300 --> 00:55:18.920
Interleave your document windows,
and it makes for a whole lot easier

00:55:18.920 --> 00:55:22.570
movement of data between windows,
among other things.

00:55:24.340 --> 00:55:25.460
10 is sheets.

00:55:25.470 --> 00:55:27.500
Sheets are fantastic.

00:55:27.500 --> 00:55:30.140
They're probably one of the
things that's mentioned the most

00:55:30.140 --> 00:55:31.820
often in a review of Mac OS X.

00:55:31.820 --> 00:55:34.640
This new interface behavior,
new interface element,

00:55:34.640 --> 00:55:35.880
which is called sheets.

00:55:35.900 --> 00:55:37.820
Well really, sheets are just dialogues.

00:55:37.820 --> 00:55:41.420
They're document-specific
modal dialogues.

00:55:41.420 --> 00:55:44.680
So wherever today you have a document,
when you have a document open,

00:55:44.680 --> 00:55:48.040
you would bring up a dialogue
whose contents and whose settings

00:55:48.040 --> 00:55:50.780
affect the current document,
the active document,

00:55:50.780 --> 00:55:53.580
that's a perfect candidate for a sheet.

00:55:53.580 --> 00:55:57.040
And the benefit of sheets is that
it moves the user into a more

00:55:57.040 --> 00:56:02.300
modeless world where they become
modal only for that document.

00:56:02.320 --> 00:56:04.760
Today, in most cases,
if you put up a modal

00:56:04.760 --> 00:56:08.560
dialogue for a document,
I'm now forced into this

00:56:08.570 --> 00:56:10.020
modality within the application.

00:56:10.020 --> 00:56:11.200
I'm modal for that application.

00:56:11.200 --> 00:56:13.820
I can't do anything else in
that application on Mac OS 9.

00:56:13.820 --> 00:56:16.840
Sheets allow me to put up the sheet,
this dialogue,

00:56:16.840 --> 00:56:19.890
that is connected with the title
bar of a document so that there's

00:56:19.890 --> 00:56:21.120
this immediate association.

00:56:21.120 --> 00:56:24.360
I can move that window around and
the sheet just follows along with it.

00:56:24.360 --> 00:56:27.310
And yet I can still interact with all
the other documents and work on the other

00:56:27.340 --> 00:56:29.450
documents in the application that I'm on.

00:56:30.520 --> 00:56:33.040
So this is a move,
a deliberate move on our part to

00:56:33.040 --> 00:56:36.430
move even more closely to some of the
design principles that are laid out,

00:56:36.520 --> 00:56:39.280
software design principles that
are in the beginning of the human

00:56:39.280 --> 00:56:40.700
interface guidelines document.

00:56:41.140 --> 00:56:43.580
I know a lot of people that just
sort of open that book and they go,

00:56:43.700 --> 00:56:46.280
software design principles.

00:56:47.890 --> 00:56:49.500
Oh,
that's what a button needs to look like.

00:56:49.500 --> 00:56:51.280
And they go on and they
make the widgets look right,

00:56:51.280 --> 00:56:54.560
and yet they haven't paid any attention
to the software design principles.

00:56:54.560 --> 00:56:57.520
Here's a great example of how we are
paying attention to the software design

00:56:57.630 --> 00:57:00.100
principles in Mac OS X with Aqua,
and moving one of those

00:57:00.110 --> 00:57:01.560
principles is mode-lessness.

00:57:01.560 --> 00:57:04.570
Don't force users into a mode where
they're stuck and they can't do anything

00:57:04.600 --> 00:57:07.120
else but what they're focused on.

00:57:07.120 --> 00:57:08.000
Sheets does that.

00:57:08.030 --> 00:57:11.090
So use Sheets only where
it's document specific.

00:57:11.820 --> 00:57:12.260
Help tags.

00:57:12.260 --> 00:57:15.600
Help tags is another,
is the next level of user

00:57:15.600 --> 00:57:16.850
assistance on Mac OS X.

00:57:16.880 --> 00:57:19.380
HTML help is really just
delivery of content,

00:57:19.380 --> 00:57:19.620
right?

00:57:19.620 --> 00:57:22.200
It's sort of like, I need to read about,
you know, making a movie,

00:57:22.200 --> 00:57:23.560
or whatever it is that you do.

00:57:23.560 --> 00:57:26.370
And so the user goes off and reads
the HTML document and looks at

00:57:26.370 --> 00:57:29.250
some interactive stuff and hears
some sound clips or whatever it is.

00:57:29.310 --> 00:57:30.920
But help tags are all
about sort of saying,

00:57:30.920 --> 00:57:34.540
letting the user move
around the screen and say,

00:57:34.540 --> 00:57:37.100
let's see, what's this?

00:57:37.210 --> 00:57:37.630
Ah.

00:57:37.630 --> 00:57:39.410
What's this?

00:57:39.720 --> 00:57:40.300
Oh, okay.

00:57:40.370 --> 00:57:41.620
So it's, what's this?

00:57:41.620 --> 00:57:42.460
User assistance.

00:57:42.460 --> 00:57:47.150
And the interface guidelines
talk in great detail about how to

00:57:47.360 --> 00:57:49.730
write the content for a help tag.

00:57:49.730 --> 00:57:52.800
It's pretty straightforward,
and help tags go a long way

00:57:52.800 --> 00:57:55.840
in providing a really rich,
really informative user

00:57:55.840 --> 00:57:57.380
experience for your customers.

00:57:59.900 --> 00:58:02.310
Speech Enabling:
We've come a long way with our

00:58:02.310 --> 00:58:04.140
speech technologies at Apple.

00:58:04.160 --> 00:58:07.000
There's a session here
called Session 127.

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:09.340
It's speech recognition and synthesis.

00:58:09.340 --> 00:58:10.110
We all talk.

00:58:10.110 --> 00:58:11.000
We all listen.

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:14.390
These are things that we
don't even think about doing.

00:58:14.570 --> 00:58:17.860
Wouldn't it be great if your application
could enhance the user experience by

00:58:17.860 --> 00:58:20.270
speaking to the user where it made sense?

00:58:20.380 --> 00:58:22.080
Say you're in K-12.

00:58:22.080 --> 00:58:24.060
Say you deliver educational products.

00:58:24.130 --> 00:58:29.050
Or say you're a graphic design tool
and you want to just... Right now,

00:58:29.050 --> 00:58:31.310
you say you're drawing something.

00:58:31.350 --> 00:58:33.220
In today's applications,
if you're drawing something,

00:58:33.220 --> 00:58:36.600
the mouse button is down
and that's my input device.

00:58:36.650 --> 00:58:39.300
Wouldn't it be cool if
I could say while I'm drawing,

00:58:39.370 --> 00:58:40.710
"Thicker pen.

00:58:40.890 --> 00:58:42.590
Color red."

00:58:43.090 --> 00:58:44.220
That's another input device.

00:58:44.220 --> 00:58:47.300
And the speech technologies
at Apple allow you to do that.

00:58:47.450 --> 00:58:50.800
And so think about ways in Mac OS X,
all of the APIs and all the functionality

00:58:50.800 --> 00:58:54.100
that was there before is available in 10,
and we're going to extend this

00:58:54.160 --> 00:58:56.180
stuff further as we're going
to do a lot of other stuff.

00:58:56.240 --> 00:58:59.660
So speech enabling your application
can greatly enhance the user

00:58:59.670 --> 00:59:03.520
experience and make you even a
better full class citizen or a better

00:59:03.520 --> 00:59:07.400
citizen in the country of Mac OS X,
in this world of Mac OS X.

00:59:07.400 --> 00:59:10.600
Not only speech recognition,
which sometimes is difficult

00:59:10.610 --> 00:59:13.170
to do and get right,
given the environment that your

00:59:13.260 --> 00:59:15.480
product is used in or whatever,
but speech synthesis

00:59:15.480 --> 00:59:17.260
is actually fantastic.

00:59:17.320 --> 00:59:22.120
You can actually embed in the text string
that you give to the speech synthesizer,

00:59:22.120 --> 00:59:24.880
you know,
little codes that say emphasize,

00:59:24.880 --> 00:59:28.940
change the intonation, pause,
so that the speech synthesis

00:59:28.940 --> 00:59:31.720
you get is actually very,
very realistic.

00:59:31.780 --> 00:59:35.340
So imagine you're a K through
12 customer and you want to

00:59:35.340 --> 00:59:36.300
use speech in your product.

00:59:36.380 --> 00:59:39.210
You can actually greatly enhance
the user experience by having this

00:59:39.360 --> 00:59:40.660
