00:59:40.660 --> 00:59:43.610
Or if you're a game developer,
instead of storing tons

00:59:43.610 --> 00:59:47.880
and tons or megabytes and
megabytes of digitized speaking,

00:59:47.880 --> 00:59:51.310
you know, digitized voices,
use speech synthesis.

00:59:51.320 --> 00:59:54.570
You just have to store the ASCII text
of the string that the synthesizer

00:59:54.570 --> 00:59:58.040
would speak with some of the,
you know, encodings inside and you'd

00:59:58.040 --> 01:00:00.940
save tons of space on your CD,
which would in turn translate into

01:00:00.940 --> 01:00:02.480
lower cost of goods and et cetera,
et cetera.

01:00:02.480 --> 01:00:05.720
So speech enabling your application
can make sense in a lot of cases.

01:00:08.410 --> 01:00:10.800
The last final building block,
which wasn't on the chart in the

01:00:10.800 --> 01:00:13.480
beginning but I want to mention,
