fonts and stuff like that,

01:02:17.820 --> 01:02:19.040
for your text.

01:02:19.140 --> 01:02:20.180
Application bundles.

01:02:20.180 --> 01:02:24.590
That point is up there because it's about
the double click experience on Mac OS X.

01:02:25.780 --> 01:02:30.170
Remember years gone by back in '84
when Mac Paint was just a single file?

01:02:30.180 --> 01:02:33.540
This application that we all love to use,
it was a single file on the desktop.

01:02:33.540 --> 01:02:36.760
It was in a folder and you just
double-clicked it and that was all.

01:02:36.760 --> 01:02:38.840
And if you wanted to move
it to another system,

01:02:38.930 --> 01:02:41.190
your new Macintosh,
you just copied it on a floppy

01:02:41.240 --> 01:02:42.170
disk and moved it across.

01:02:42.180 --> 01:02:43.620
It was just one icon to move.

01:02:43.670 --> 01:02:46.840
Mac OS X not only does it provide
bundles that give you a single

01:02:46.840 --> 01:02:50.500
icon that users move around,
and that icon is really just a

01:02:50.530 --> 01:02:52.910
